 hunting of animals became the chief recreation of military officers and civilian officials, a source of display and symbolic dominance of the environment. Imperial hunting fed the natural history craze of the day, and many hunters collected trophies and specimens for private and public collections as well as contributing to hunting literature. Adopting a radical approach to issues of conservation, this book links the hunting cult in Africa and India to the development of conservation, and consolidates widely-scattered material on the importance of hunting to the economics and nutrition of African societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHuntingxHistory. 0aHuntingzGreat BritainxHistory. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  aAfrican societies.  aCentral Africa.  aEast Africa.  aIndian Civil Service.  aMzilikazi.  aRomanticism.  aSouth Africa.  aglobal power.  agreat hunters.  ahunting mentality.  aimperial power.  ainter-war years.  anineteenth-century hunting cult.  apre-colonial economy.  awhite settlement.  awild predators.1 aMacKenzie, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611958240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526119582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526119582/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles